        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "6. Suppose that an experiment is conducted to measure a constant $\\theta$ . Independent unbiased measurements $y$ of $\\theta$ can be made with either of two instruments, both of which measure with normal errors: for $i = 1 , 2$ , instrument $i$ produces independent errors with a $N ( 0 , \\sigma _ { i } ^ { 2 } )$ distribution. The two error variances $\\sigma _ { 1 } ^ { 2 }$ and $\\sigma _ { 2 } ^ { 2 }$ are known. When a measurement $y$ is made, a record is kept of the instrument used so that after $n$ measurements the data is $( a _ { 1 } , y _ { 1 } ) , \\dotsc , ( a _ { n } , y _ { n } )$ , where $a _ { m } = i$ if $y _ { m }$ is obtained using instrument $i$ . The choice between instruments is made independently for each observation in such a way that ",
        "bbox": [
            191,
            718,
            803,
            866
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nP (a _ {m} = 1) = P (a _ {m} = 2) = 0. 5, \\quad 1 \\leq m \\leq n.\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
